record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 5 GENERAL TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (TS-1) This service is available to any party who contracts with the Company to provide transportation service of (1) Gas produced in Georgia from a landfill Gas production site or produced from natural underground strata containing natural gas; (2) LNG that is vaporized in Georgia to become Gas; or, (3) other forms of Gas produced or that may be produced in Georgia; provided that all Gas shall conform to the Companys Gas Quality specifications. The Company shall transport Gas on a Firm basis from a Transportation Service Receipt Point to a Transportation Service Delivery Point. To be eligible for inclusion as a Transportation Service Receipt Point in a Transportation Service Agreement, there must be a valid, effective transportation service agreement in place between the Company and the Point Operator of that Transportation Service Receipt Point. Subject to the Company having available capacity and the ability to offer defined amounts of Firm transportation service of Gas, the Company shall offer Firm transportation service on a non-discriminatory basis to all Customers that meet the eligibility criteria set forth in this Statement of Operating Conditions. This Transportation Service will be available on existing facilities of the Company except as otherwise agreed. The Company shall not be required, at its own expense, to install any facilities of any kind to serve a Customer under this Statement of Operating Conditions. In the event that any new or altered facilities are required to serve a Customer, said Customer shall execute a facilities construction contract, that may be part of the Transportation Service Agreement required herein, and shall pay for all costs of additional facilities, including without limitation storage, distribution, and metering facilities. All transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be undertaken on behalf of an interstate pipeline company or an LDC served by an interstate pipeline. To be considered on behalf of the specified entities, there must be an interstate pipeline or an LDC (other than the Company) that either (1) has physical custody of and transports the natural gas at some point, or (2) holds title to the natural gas at some point, which may occur prior to, during, or after the time that the gas is being transported by the Company, for a purpose related to its status and functions as an interstate pipeline or LDC, as applicable. The Company reserves the right not to offer or commence service or to discontinue any service when, in the Companys sole discretion, any impairment of its firm services, including its ability to use storage to support firm services and gas purchases for firm services, would or may result. The Company also reserves the right to file with the FERC to modify this Statement of Operating Conditions as it deems necessary and appropriate at any time in the future.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 2 INTRODUCTORY STATEMENT This Statement of Operating Conditions specifies the terms and conditions pursuant to which Atlanta Gas Light Company (Company), a natural gas distribution company, shall provide firm transportation service on a non-discriminatory basis pursuant to Section 284.224 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commissions (FERC) rules and regulations (18 C.F.R. § 284.224). These transportation services will be provided for parties that deliver gas to the Companys facilities for transportation by the Company and redelivery to points within Georgia where the Companys facilities interconnect with the facilities of an interstate natural gas pipeline company, and where the ultimate consumption of the natural gas so transported by the Company will be outside the State of Georgia. The Company owns and operates a natural gas delivery company and provides retail natural gas delivery services to customers located throughout the State of Georgia, including the Atlanta metropolitan area. The Companys rates and tariffs are subject to regulation by the Georgia Public Service Commission (Georgia PSC). The Company sought and received from the FERC a blanket certificate of public convenience and necessity to provide interstate transportation services pursuant to Section 284.224 of the Commissions rules and regulations, by order issued on January 23, 1998 under Docket No. CP97-772-000. Pursuant to that authority, and subject to further approval of the Companys rates as necessary, the Company is authorized to sell, transport, and assign natural gas in interstate commerce subject to the jurisdiction of FERC to the same extent and in the same manner that intrastate pipelines are authorized to engage in such activities by sections 311 and 312 of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 (82 FERC ¶ 62,045 (1998)). Pursuant to applicable FERC regulations, the Company is utilizing, for blanket certificate service, the transportation rates and Lost and Unaccounted for Gas retainage percentage approved by the Georgia PSC for comparable intrastate service.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 6 REQUESTS AND CONTRACTING FOR SERVICE An application for transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be made by a written request which shall be accompanied by the appropriate application fee as set forth in Section 3, Statement of Rates. No application fee shall be required for the extension or renewal of an existing transportation service agreement, but shall be required upon application to substantially amend an existing agreement. An application for service shall be deemed to be valid if it specifies: (i) the exact legal name of the Person requesting service; (ii) the type of service requested; (iii) the proposed rates; (iv) the proposed term of the service agreement; (v) the proposed Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) and the proposed Transportation Service Delivery Point(s); and (vi) other proposed terms and conditions. The Company shall tender a service agreement upon its acceptance of the Persons application for transportation service. All service under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall require the execution of a Transportation Service Agreement by the Customer and the Company. A request for service shall not be valid and the Company shall not be required to grant any such request for service if: (a) the Person requesting service does not meet the Companys creditworthiness criteria as set forth in Section 7; (b) the service requested would require the construction, modification, expansion or acquisition of any facilities; (c) the service requested would not comply with this Statement of Operating Conditions; (d) there is a lack of adequate capacity to perform the requested service; (e) accepting the request would require the Company to change its jurisdictional status; (f) there is no service agreement in place between the Company and the Point Operator at the Transportation Service Receipt Point requested by Customer; or (g) the service requested is at less than the applicable maximum rate; provided, however, that the Company may agree to provide service under this Statement of Operating Conditions at less than the applicable maximum rate.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 16 CURTAILMENT Any Transportation Service furnished by the Company may be curtailed in whole or in part by the Company at any time and from time to time in such manner as the Company may elect when the same becomes necessary in the judgment of the Company by reason of an event of Force Majeure or to accomplish any of the following: a. To protect essential human need uses, such as residences, hospitals, residential institutions, schools, etc.; b. To implement curtailment or load control plans permitted to become effective, or ordered by, the Georgia PSC or by any other governmental body or agency having jurisdiction with respect to the Company; and c. To protect the operational integrity of the Companys system. Customers Scheduled Daily Transportation Quantity shall be curtailed on a pro rata basis with the Companys other firm obligations at the affected Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) or Transportation Service Delivery Point(s). The Company will give notice of curtailment of any particular service that is reasonable under the circumstances. In the event that a Customer fails to comply with any curtailment notice or order of the Company reducing the Customers hourly or daily use of any transportation service provided hereunder, the Company shall have the option to terminate Customers Transportation Service Agreement and take such other action, at law and in equity, as it may deem appropriate under the circumstances to obtain relief from and indemnification for Customers failure to comply.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 15 TITLE, RESPONSIBILITY FOR GAS, INDEMNITIES Customer warrants, for itself, its successors and assigns, that it will have, at the time of delivery of Gas hereunder, good and marketable title to the Gas delivered, or it will otherwise have the right to deliver such Gas, and that such Gas shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances, and claims. Customer warrants that it will indemnify the Company and save it harmless from suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses and expenses arising from or out of adverse claims of any and all persons to said Gas or to royalties, taxes, license fees or charges thereon. As between Customer and the Company, Customer shall be in control and possession of the Gas prior to delivery to the Company at the Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) and after redelivery to or for the account of Customer at the Transportation Service Delivery Point(s), and Customer shall indemnify and hold the Company harmless from any damage or injury caused thereby. The Company shall be in control and possession of the Gas after the delivery of the same at the Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) and until redelivery by the Company to or for the account of Customer at the Transportation Service Delivery Point(s), and shall indemnify and hold Customer harmless from any damage or injury caused thereby, except for damages and injuries caused by the sole negligence of Customer.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 14 BILLING AND PAYMENT The Company shall render to Customer on or before the 7th Business Day of each month a bill which sets forth the charges owed by Customer to the Company for the preceding months service. Customer shall pay the Company the amount due under any bill from the Company within ten (10) Days after receipt by the Customer of the bill from the Company. Any bill not paid within such ten (10) Day period shall bear interest at the rate of one percent (1%) per month. A Customer may dispute the amount of any bill by notifying the Company within sixty (60) Days of receipt by the Customer of the bill from the Company. If a Customer in good faith disputes the amount of any bill, the Customer shall nevertheless pay to the Company the amount of such bill and, at any time thereafter within thirty (30) Days of a demand made by the Customer, the Company shall furnish if so required a good and sufficient surety bond guaranteeing refund to the Customer upon such bills after a final determination by agreement, by determination of regulatory agencies having jurisdiction, or by judgment of the courts, as may be the case.

Except as otherwise provided herein, in the event any provision within this Statement of Operating Conditions is found to be inconsistent with or contrary to any law, order, rule or regulation, the latter shall be deemed to control and the specific, applicable provisions, to the extent possible, shall be regarded as modified accordingly and as so modified shall continue in full force and effect. The parties hereto recognize that the Company has entered into transactions hereunder based on its good faith understanding that all acts, obligations, and services performed or to be performed by the Company hereunder, and the charges therefore, are exempt from the regulation of FERC or any successor federal governmental authority, except as provided by Section 284.224 of the FERCs regulations. The Company reserves the right to terminate immediately the offering or furnishing of any service hereunder if, in the Companys sole discretion, any governmental act occurs which would require the Company to offer or furnish service hereunder other than those contemplated in the Companys Transportation Service Agreement with Customer or which would cause any impairment in the Companys ability to furnish or continue any service, or require the Company to offer additional services or require a change to the Companys jurisdictional or regulatory status.

record_data.record_narrative_name: Operational Provisions Mismatch Orders of SOC
record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 13 OPERATIONAL PROVISIONS MISMATCH ORDERS 13.1 General. When the Company anticipates that a Mismatch between supply and demand on its system may present a threat to the integrity of the Companys operations or jeopardize the Companys firm distribution service to retail customers, the Company may issue a Mismatch Order (similar to an operational flow order issued by an interstate pipeline) and Customers shall be required to comply with the restrictions specified in such Mismatch Order. Such Mismatch Order will be posted by the Company on its EBB at least four (4) hours in advance of the effective time of any restrictions specified in the Mismatch Order. It shall be the responsibility of Customer to monitor the Companys EBB daily for such orders, and the EBB posting of a Mismatch Order shall be considered due notice. Mismatch Orders will apply to all transportation services hereunder that originate or terminate in, or otherwise affect, the Pool(s) (as defined in the Companys Georgia PSC tariff) specified in the Mismatch Order. In the event that the Customer is not the Point Operator of the applicable Transportation Service Receipt Point(s), then compliance with Mismatch Orders shall be the responsibility of the Point Operator. 13.2 Demand Mismatch. When the Company determines that anticipated demands of its retail customers served from one or more Pools of its system exceed either the anticipated Gas supply or the Companys capacity in such Pool(s), the Company may designate a Demand Mismatch and, pursuant to Section 13.1, post a Mismatch Order. On any Day in which a Demand Mismatch Order is in effect, all affected Customers must comply with the Mismatch Order. If a Customer violates such Mismatch Order by delivering less Gas at its Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) than was scheduled, then Customer shall be billed at a rate of $30.00 for each Dth of deficient volumes delivered in violation of the Mismatch Order. Provided, however, if the Companys Demand Mismatch Order is the result of an SNG type 6 operational flow order, the following rates will apply in lieu of the $30.00 per Dth rate for violation of a Demand Mismatch Order: the Daily Index Cost of Gas for that Day, per Dth, plus Percentage Rate per Dth 2% No charge. > 2% < 10% The lesser of $15.00 or 1.5 times the highest Daily Index Cost of Gas for the applicable month. 10% $30.00. 13.3 Supply Mismatch. When the Company determines that anticipated Gas supply to a Pool or Pools exceeds the anticipated demands of the retail customers served from such Pool(s), the Company may designate a Supply Mismatch and, pursuant to Section 13.1, post a Mismatch Order. On any Day in which a Supply Mismatch Order is in effect, all affected Customers must comply with the Mismatch Order. If a Customer violates such Mismatch Order by delivering more Gas at its Transportation Service Receipt Point(s) than was scheduled, then Customer shall be billed at a rate of $30.00 for each Dth of excess volumes delivered in violation of the Mismatch Order. Provided, however, if the Companys Supply Mismatch Order is the result of an SNG type 6 operational flow order, the following rates will apply in lieu of the $30.00 per Dth rate for violation of a Demand Mismatch Order: Percentage Rate per Dth 2% No charge. > 2% < 10% The lesser of $15.00 or 1.5 times the highest Daily Index Cost of Gas for the applicable month. 10% $30.00. 13.4 Disposition of Revenues. Revenues from Mismatch charges in excess of actual costs incurred by the Company shall be credited to the Universal Service Fund.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 9 MEASUREMENT, MEASURING EQUIPMENT Unless otherwise agreed upon, the Company shall install, maintain, and operate such Metering Equipment as necessary to accurately and reliably measure daily receipts and deliveries to and from Customers. The cost of installing Metering Equipment, including any Metering Equipment specified within a Transportation Service Agreement, shall be borne by Customer, unless otherwise expressly agreed. Customer may install, maintain, and operate, at its expense, such check measuring equipment as it desires, provided that such equipment shall be installed, maintained and operated so as not to interfere with the operation of Companys facilities, including Metering Equipment. Where orifice meters are used, volumes of Gas delivered shall be computed in accordance with formulae, tables and methods prescribed in Orifice Metering of Natural Gas, Gas Measurement Committee Report No. 3 of the American Gas Association published April 1955, reprinted with revisions in February 1991. Said volumes shall be corrected for daily average flowing temperature to the extent such temperature deviates from 60o F and for specific gravity. Where rotary or turbine type meters are used on installations where the Customers annual usage is more than 300,000 Dth, all volumes of Gas measured by such meters shall be corrected to a base temperature of 60o Fahrenheit. For the purpose of measurement hereunder, when Gas is delivered at a pressure in excess of 14.73 PSIA, such volumes of Gas shall be corrected to a pressure of 14.73 PSIA. It is assumed that the atmospheric pressure is 14.4 pounds per square inch. The measurement of Gas volumes shall be adjusted for deviation from Boyles Law in accordance with generally accepted engineering practices through positive displacement meters at a pressure not in excess of 20 PSIG, and the Gas shall be assumed to obey Boyles Law.

record_data.record_narrative_name: Nominations, Confirmation and Scheduling of SOC
record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 8 NOMINATIONS, CONFIRMATION AND SCHEDULING All nominations shall be submitted via the EBB. The deadlines for nominations, including the deadline for intra-Day nominations, shall be the same as the respective deadlines for parallel nominations on the Relevant Pipeline. A nomination shall specify separately the volumes to be delivered at each Transportation Service Delivery Point on the Relevant Pipeline. On any Day that it desires transportation service under an effective Transportation Service Agreement, Customer shall nominate a quantity up to but not in excess of its Maximum Daily Transportation Quantity. The Company will confirm nominations and reserves the right not to confirm a nomination in whole or in part if, in the sole judgment of the Company, confirmation of the nomination might threaten the operational integrity of its system. If any nomination to the Company does not match the corresponding nomination to the Point Operator or Relevant Pipeline, the Company may change the nomination to match that to Point Operator or the Relevant Pipeline, as applicable, and shall post any such change on the EBB. The confirmed nomination shall be the Customers Scheduled Daily Transportation Quantity. Confirmed nominations will be scheduled for receipt on the Companys system consistently with the scheduling procedures of the Relevant Pipeline.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 12 BALANCING The Customer shall balance the quantity of Gas scheduled for transportation service with the quantity of Gas actually delivered by Customer to the Company at the Transportation Service Receipt Point(s). Failure to balance may result in the penalties described below. In the event that the Customer is not the Point Operator of the applicable Transportation Service Receipt Point(s), then the Point Operator shall be responsible for balancing the Gas quantities on behalf of Customer on the terms set forth herein. Daily Balancing The Company shall calculate daily charges for balancing services performed by the Company for a Customer. Customers will be balanced on a daily basis. The rates applicable to the volumes subject to a daily balancing charge are based upon the percentage that such volumes for each Customer on a Day, whether positive or negative, are of the actual deliveries from a Customer to its retail customers on such Day. The rate per Dth shall apply to the total amount of all imbalance volumes so determined and are as follows: Percent Rate per Dth 5% $0.00 >5% $0.07 Monthly Balancing At the end of each Month, any Customer imbalance shall be subject to the following provisions: Within three (3) consecutive Days following the end of month closing period for each month, the Company shall post on the EBB each Customers imbalance whether positive or negative. Following such posting, the Company shall provide a period of three (3) consecutive Days during which period Customers may trade positive and negative imbalances via the EBB. If, following the trading period, the Customer has any imbalance remaining, whether positive or negative, such imbalance shall be cashed out as follows: (a) Negative Imbalance 0% 4% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times 1.20 >4% 10% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times 1.30 >10% 20% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times 1.40 >20% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times 1.50 Plus the 100% load factor transportation rate, applicable surcharges and fuel on the Relevant Pipeline. (b) Positive Imbalance 0% 4% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times .80 >4% 10% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times .70 >10% 20% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times .60 > 20% Average Daily Index Cost of Gas for the Month times .50 Plus the 100% load factor transportation rate, applicable surcharges and fuel on the Relevant Pipeline.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 4 DEFINITION OF TERMS Business Day: Any Day from Monday through Friday inclusive, excluding any holiday observed by the Company. Company: Atlanta Gas Light Company. Customer: A Person that has contracted with the Company for the provision of service pursuant to the Companys FERC Blanket Certificate. Daily Index Cost of Gas: The wellhead price of Gas per Dth available for delivery to a Relevant Pipeline on a particular Day which, unless the Georgia PSC directs otherwise, shall be the price for Gas delivered into the Relevant Pipeline on such Day, as determined below from the Daily Price Survey set forth in Gas Daily, published by The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc., in the first issue of such publication following the date of the transaction. For Transcontinental Gas Pipe Line Company, LLC, this price is found under the heading Louisiana Onshore South, in the row entitled Transco Z3 St. 50, 62, 65, and the column entitled Midpoint. For Southern Natural Gas Company, this price is found under the heading Louisiana Onshore South, in the row entitled Sonat and the column entitled Midpoint. If any of the above references ceases to be published, or ceases to be published in the format described herein, the Company shall designate an alternative publication or format and, upon notification of such designation to the Georgia PSC, the alternative designated shall be effective for the purposes hereof unless the Georgia PSC directs otherwise. Day: The period of 24 consecutive hours beginning at 10:00 a.m., Eastern Clock Time. Demand Mismatch: A Mismatch that occurs when the anticipated demands of retail customers served from a Pool or Pools exceeds either the anticipated Gas supply to the Company or the Companys capacity in such Pool or Pools. Electronic Bulletin Board (EBB): An interactive electronic communication system that, among other things, allows parties to view gas-related information, make nominations, offer bids, and receive confirmations. FERC: Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. FERC Blanket Certificate: The limited jurisdiction certificate of public convenience and necessity issued by FERC to the Company in Docket No. CP97-772-000. Firm: A type of Transportation Service that ordinarily is not subject to interruption or curtailment. Gas or Natural Gas: Any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and noncombustible gases in a gaseous state, consisting predominantly of methane. Georgia PSC: The Georgia Public Service Commission. LDC: Local Distribution Company. Liquefied Natural Gas or LNG: Gas that has been converted from a gaseous state to liquid form. Lost and Unaccounted for Gas: Gas that is lost through the normal operation of the Companys system. Maximum Daily Transportation Quantity: The quantity of Gas that the Customer shall be entitled to nominate for transportation service pursuant to and as set forth in the Customers Transportation Service Agreement. Metering Equipment: All piping, fittings, meters and equipment necessary to meter a gas service, as determined by the Company. Mismatch: A situation when either the anticipated Gas supply to a Pool or Pools or the Companys capacity in such Pool or Pools will not match the anticipated demands of the Companys retail customers served from such Pool or Pools. Mismatch Order: An order by the Company to affected Customers that, due to an anticipated Demand Mismatch or Supply Mismatch, such Customers are required to take the action specified by the Company in the order. Point Operator: The entity that operates a Transportation Service Receipt Point. Person: Any corporation, whether public or private; company; individual; firm; partnership; or association. Pools: Areas of the Companys gas distribution system that are defined to facilitate the operation of the Companys system pursuant to the provisions of the Georgia Natural Gas Competition and Deregulation Act. The Company has three types of Pool Basic, Primary, and Aggregate, and further describes and identifies such Pools at Section 12 and other relevant sections of its Georgia PSC Tariff. PSIA: Pounds per square inch absolute. PSIG: Pounds per square inch gauge. Relevant Pipeline: The interstate gas pipeline company whose facilities are interconnected with those of the Company at the Transportation Service Delivery Point. Scheduled Daily Transportation Quantity: The quantity of Gas that Customer has nominated and that the Company has confirmed for transportation service under an effective Transportation Service Agreement. SNG: Southern Natural Gas Company, an interstate gas pipeline company. Supply Mismatch: A Mismatch that occurs when the anticipated Gas supply to a Pool or Pools exceeds the anticipated demands of the retail customers served from such Pool or Pools. Tariff: All Rate Schedules, Terms of Service, and Rules and Regulations approved by the Georgia PSC relating to Transportation Service by the Company. Transportation Service: Activities performed by the Company for Customer pursuant to Companys FERC Blanket Certificate, including receiving gas at a Transportation Service Receipt Point, transporting gas through the Companys system, and delivering gas to a Transportation Service Delivery Point. Transportation Service Delivery Point: The location on the Companys system where the Companys distribution system interconnects with an interstate pipeline company, and to which the Company delivers Gas to or for the account of the Customer. Transportation Service Receipt Point: As determined by the Company, the location on the Companys system where the Customer delivers Gas to be transported by the Company to a Transportation Service Delivery Point. Transportation Service Agreement: An agreement between the Company and Customer that specifies the terms of any Transportation Service provided pursuant to the Companys FERC Blanket Certificate. Universal Service Fund: The fund created by the Georgia PSC pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 46-4-161.

record_data.record_plain_text: 1150303v1 SECTION 20 PASS-THROUGH OF COSTS AND CHARGES Any costs or charges that are imposed by federal or state statute, or by any order, rule or regulation of any federal or state agency with respect to Transportation Service by the Company may be passed through by the Company to the particular Customers who received the service that gave rise to the incurrence of the cost or charge. The Company shall file to update its Statement of Operating Conditions to include such additional costs or charges. Unless otherwise specified in Customers Transportation Service Agreement, Customer shall be responsible for, and to the extent assessed directly to and paid by the Company shall reimburse the Company for, these charges including any sales, gross receipts, franchise, excise, privilege, occupation, or other tax, whether imposed by statute, ordinance, or franchise contract that the Company pays to any governmental body, based on or determined by, the transportation and delivery of Gas.

record_data.record_plain_text: SECTION 7 CREDITWORTHINESS REQUIREMENTS As a condition of eligibility for Transportation Service, Customer shall be required to establish, to the Companys satisfaction, and shall be required to provide proof of its creditworthiness. The Company shall be entitled to undertake such credit searches as it deems necessary and appropriate and to require that it receive sufficient information to establish that the potential customer is creditworthy. The results of such creditworthiness checks should generally be communicated to the potential customer within two (2) weeks of receipt of the completed application. If the potential customer is sufficiently creditworthy, no security shall be required. If a potential customer cannot establish that it is creditworthy, the creditworthiness requirements can nonetheless be satisfied by the posting of appropriate security acceptable to the Company. The amount of security required shall be determined by the Company based on the factors of the potential customers asset base and financial strength and the level of service requested. The maximum amount of security that may be required shall be the sum of (1) the total estimated charges for three (3) full months of transportation service, (2) the outstanding balance of any amounts owed by Customer to the Company, and (3) any additional facilities construction costs incurred by the Company on behalf of Customer, whether or not such amounts have become due and payable by Customer. The Company will have the right to require additional security within three (3) Business Days notice if conditions for the potential customer or Customer changes in any material way. The types of security that may be required by the Company are: security deposits; irrevocable letters of credit; guarantees; or such other security as is acceptable to Owner. A deposit may be required to be paid by a Customer at the time the transportation service agreement is executed equal to the total estimated charges for the first three (3) full months of transportation service. The terms of the deposit arrangements shall be included in the transportation service agreement. The Company can modify any and all security requirements based upon changes in the potential customers or Customers level of Transportation Service. All of the Companys creditworthiness review standards and requirements shall be imposed on a non-discriminatory basis. Security shall no longer be required where the Company deems that security is no longer needed or when the Customer is no longer receiving Transportation Service from the Company.
